Windows:
 ** Event ID 4625 â€“ Failed logon attempt.
 ** Event ID 4624 â€“ Successful logon.
 ** Event ID 4672 â€“ Special privileges assigned to a new logon.

ğŸ”§ Attack Simulation
To simulate a brute force attack and test Wazuhâ€™s detection capabilities, I used Hydra, a fast and flexible login cracker.

ğŸ” Command Used:
hydra -l user_name -P password.txt rdp://192.168.X.X
 ** -l user_name: specifies the target username
 ** -P password.txt: supplies a list of potential passwords
 ** rdp://192.168.X.X: defines the target RDP service and IP address

This generated multiple authentication attempts against a Windows system over Remote Desktop Protocol (RDP).

âš™ï¸ Detection Using Wazuh Built-In Rules
Wazuhâ€™s default ruleset successfully detected the brute force activity through the following rule IDs:

** 60122 â€“ Logs each failed login (Event ID 4625)
  â€œLogon Failure â€“ Unknown user or bad passwordâ€
 ** 60204 â€“ Aggregates multiple 4625 events into a brute force detection
   â€œMultiple Windows Logon Failuresâ€
